<?xml version='1.0' encoding='utf-8'?>
<rdf:RDF xmlns:owl="http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#" xmlns:rdf="http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#" xmlns:rdfs="http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#" xmlns:skos="http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#">
  <rdf:Description rdf:about="https://w3id.org/semanticarts/ns/ontology/gist/Component">
    <rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class" />
    <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">DEFINITION: Something that, while having an independent existence, is inherently part of or designed to be part of a larger entity, such as a system or network.</rdfs:comment>
    <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">NOTE: A component may be designed or intended as part of a whole without actually being so; e.g., a car steering wheel that is not installed in any car.</rdfs:comment>
    <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">NOTE: Many things are in a trivial sense a part of a larger thing, but are not considered components because they are not inherently part of that larger thing. For example, while a book may be part of a library (a collection of books), it is not inherently so, and thus is not a component. A playing card, on the other hand, could be considered a component in (member of) a deck of cards. This may be use case-dependent; e.g., car parts might be modeled as components in an automobile manufacturing context but not in a retail auto parts store.</rdfs:comment>
    <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">NOTE: Physical substances, such as ingredients in a cake batter, do not meet the independent existence criterion, so are not components.</rdfs:comment>
    <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">NOTE: This class is not disjoint with gist:Composite, because a component may itself break down into smaller components.</rdfs:comment>
    <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">NOTE: This is an abstract class that is not directly instantiated. Users will define subclasses that are meaningful to their domain of interest.</rdfs:comment>
    <rdfs:isDefinedBy rdf:resource="https://w3id.org/semanticarts/ontology/gistCore14.1.0" />
    <rdfs:label rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Component</rdfs:label>
    <owl:disjointWith rdf:resource="https://w3id.org/semanticarts/ns/ontology/gist/PhysicalSubstance" />
    <skos:definition rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Something that, while having an independent existence, is inherently part of or designed to be part of a larger entity, such as a system or network.</skos:definition>
    <skos:prefLabel rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Component</skos:prefLabel>
    <skos:scopeNote rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">A component may be designed or intended as part of a whole without actually being so; e.g., a car steering wheel that is not installed in any car.</skos:scopeNote>
    <skos:scopeNote rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Many things are in a trivial sense a part of a larger thing, but are not considered components because they are not inherently part of that larger thing. For example, while a book may be part of a library (a collection of books), it is not inherently so, and thus is not a component. A playing card, on the other hand, could be considered a component in (member of) a deck of cards. This may be use case-dependent; e.g., car parts might be modeled as components in an automobile manufacturing context but not in a retail auto parts store.</skos:scopeNote>
    <skos:scopeNote rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">Physical substances, such as ingredients in a cake batter, do not meet the independent existence criterion, so are not components.</skos:scopeNote>
    <skos:scopeNote rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">This class is not disjoint with gist:Composite, because a component may itself break down into smaller components.</skos:scopeNote>
    <skos:scopeNote rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string">This is an abstract class that is not directly instantiated. Users will define subclasses that are meaningful to their domain of interest.</skos:scopeNote>
  </rdf:Description>
